      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Doleo</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> I feel extremely compelled to answer this question since it happens to be asked a lot.  </P><P>I duel a lot.  I find practice makes you better at it and I just enjoy the challenge, so here is the info on exp loss.</P><P>Long ago, yes, a dot would result in exp lost, but many patches ago this was corrected.  Pets no longer take exp either.  I have tested this on many "volunteers" over and over, and I have also tested it on a seperate account dueling one of my own characters.</P><P>Your dueling opponent will STILL LOSE EXP int the following situation:</P><P>If he dies to a dot or pet while you have him feared, and not one of your nukes he or she will lose exp.  The reason is because the player is in a LD/NPC mode at that time, so will exp death just as a LD kill would be.</P><P>Gladly, I rarely have this problem because of the way I have found is most effective in duels.  Never fear your opponent, simply shadowstep and fight as you normally would without fearing.</P><P>My duel approach against most classes, is as follows:</P><P>Begin the fight with any pet you like, pets don't hit PCs very well, so it's merely a distraction ;).  The player is likely to come running straight for you, shadowstep.  Find your opponent and within spell casting range put  Vexing Mordinia or Bond of Death on them.  I then shadowstep again.  Find opponent again, who by now is getting backstabed by my rogue pet, and apply splurt.  Shadowstep, change robes.  Dressed in your new different looking robe, lifetap, I like deflux for the speed.  Shadowstep, change robes.  </P><P>Never try to root.  Never try using anything except irresistable spells.  </P><P>I have found this method never causes exp loss, I rarely loose a duel, and my record was a cocky bard that died in under 30 secs.</P><P>Good luck, hope this helps answer your question.</P><P></P><P></P><P> </font></td>
      </tr>
